---
/**
 * Fred Munzenmaier — JockShock Founder Plan
 *
 * Internal page behind /admin gate. Direct, founder-to-founder register.
 * Math is sourced from Nexus DB (lmtjxckdcsdymqxpgjxo) as of 2026-05-06.
 * Numbers will move when BOMs change — Nexus is the source of truth, not
 * this page. The monthly commission report is the binding number.
 *
 * Definitions (locked with Mike 2026-05-06):
 *   - Commission basis = contribution margin = revenue − COGS − Shopify
 *     fee (2.9% + $0.30). Shipping is paid by the customer, not deducted.
 *   - Fred's rate = 20% of contribution margin
 *   - Subscriptions: recurring commission for the life of the sub, every
 *     shipment, no expiration. 10% subscription discount applies to retail.
 *
 * Style: "He's worked here before. He gets it." Don't over-explain line
 * items. Show the number that hits his account. Point at Nexus for the
 * audit trail. Aaron voice but tightened for an insider audience.
 *
 * Claims register: JockShock is a deodorizer. Never reintroduce kill /
 * antimicrobial / disinfectant / EPA / 24HR / residual claims here, even
 * in internal copy — Fred uses this to brief gyms and we don't want him
 * accidentally repeating language we don't substantiate.
 */
import AdminLayout from "../../layouts/AdminLayout.astro";

// Snapshot of Nexus pricing/COGS as of 2026-05-06. This is shown as a
// reference table in the page; the live number Fred is paid against is
// always the Nexus monthly commission report.
const SNAPSHOT_DATE = "2026-05-06";

const SHOPIFY_FEE_PCT = 0.029;
const SHOPIFY_FEE_FLAT = 0.30;
const FRED_RATE = 0.20;

interface Sku {
  label: string;
  retail: number;
  cogs: number;
}

const jockshock: Sku[] = [
  { label: "32oz Starter", retail: 24.99, cogs: 4.78 },
  { label: "3-pack Athlete", retail: 59.99, cogs: 14.34 },
  { label: "6-pack Team", retail: 99.99, cogs: 28.68 },
];

const zeropoint: Sku[] = [
  { label: "ZeroPoint 4×1G Case", retail: 96.0, cogs: 33.39 },
  { label: "ZeroPoint 2×2.5G Case", retail: 99.0, cogs: 40.63 },
];

function commission(sku: Sku, discount = 0): {
  sale: number;
  margin: number;
  fred: number;
} {
  const sale = sku.retail * (1 - discount);
  const fee = sale * SHOPIFY_FEE_PCT + SHOPIFY_FEE_FLAT;
  const margin = sale - sku.cogs - fee;
  return {
    sale,
    margin,
    fred: margin * FRED_RATE,
  };
}

const $ = (n: number) =>
  n.toLocaleString("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD" });
---

<AdminLayout title="Fred — Founder Plan" activeNav="/admin/fred/">
  <p style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.14em; margin-bottom: 8px;">
    Internal · For Fred Munzenmaier · fmunzjr@gmail.com
  </p>
  <h1 style="font-size: 36px; line-height: 1.1; margin-bottom: 16px;">
    The JockShock Founder Plan
  </h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Hey Fred. Here's the deal. No marketing speak — just what we're building, what
    you're walking into, and what the math actually looks like for you.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>The short version.</strong> You're the founder face of the gym channel.
    Not equity, but a real commission on every bottle and every case that moves —
    forever, on subscriptions. Walk into gyms athlete-to-athlete. We do the
    fulfillment, the support, the logistics. You bring the relationships and run
    the program. Nexus generates your commission report monthly. You get paid
    monthly.
  </div>

  <h2>Founder, but not equity — and why it still pays</h2>
  <p>
    Calling you a founder isn't a vanity title. It reflects what you're actually
    going to do — be the human face of the gym channel, the one a gym owner trusts
    to talk straight about what JockShock is and how the program works. UGA running
    back, owns a D1 Training franchise, runs the program. That's the credential
    set. That story matters more in this audience than any equity number on paper.
  </p>
  <p>
    The reason it's commission and not equity: equity dilutes. Commission scales
    with what you actually move. The more you sell, the more you make, and the
    pay isn't gated by a cap table or a vesting schedule. The 20% rate is the
    same rate we give everyone on our sales team. Your upside lives in volume,
    not in a paper share.
  </p>

  <h2>What we actually sell</h2>
  <p>
    Two products, paired into one program.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>JockShock</strong> is the athlete-side spray — 32oz matte black, goes
    in the gear bag, sprayed inside pads, helmets, gloves, mouthguards, cleats
    after every practice. Pro-grade equipment deodorizer powered by ZeroPoint
    Technology.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>ZeroPoint</strong> is the facility-side product — the same chemistry
    family, sized for cleaning mats, equipment surfaces, locker rooms, water
    bottle stations. Sold to gyms in cases.
  </p>
  <p>
    Same chemistry, two formats, two use cases, one customer (the gym owner). We
    pitch them together as a single program, not two SKUs. That's the whole
    angle — the gym takes care of the facility, the athlete takes care of the
    gear, both products work the same way.
  </p>

  <div class="callout subtle">
    <strong>What we say about the chemistry.</strong> Same family of chemistry
    your immune system produces. Goes after odor at the source. Gear-safe and
    skin-safe at use concentration. Powered by ZeroPoint Technology.<br />
    <strong>What we don't say.</strong> No "kills bacteria." No "antimicrobial."
    No "disinfects." No "EPA-registered." No "24-hour protection." No claim
    about residual or duration of effect. We're a deodorizer. Stay there.
  </div>

  <h2>How the math works for you</h2>
  <p>
    You earn <strong>20% of contribution margin</strong> on every sale you drive.
    Contribution margin is what we sold it for, minus COGS, minus the Shopify
    transaction fee. Shipping is paid by the customer at checkout — not part of
    your math. Discounts come off the top before we calculate.
  </p>
  <p>
    Below is a snapshot from Nexus on {SNAPSHOT_DATE}. <strong>The live numbers
    move</strong> as costs change. The monthly Nexus report is always the
    binding number, not this table.
  </p>

  <h3>JockShock — per unit</h3>
  <table class="table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>SKU</th>
        <th class="r">Retail</th>
        <th class="r">COGS</th>
        <th class="r">Margin</th>
        <th class="r yellow">Fred 20%</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {
        jockshock.map((s) => {
          const c = commission(s);
          return (
            <tr>
              <td>{s.label}</td>
              <td class="r">{$(s.retail)}</td>
              <td class="r">{$(s.cogs)}</td>
              <td class="r">{$(c.margin)}</td>
              <td class="r yellow"><strong>{$(c.fred)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
          );
        })
      }
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>ZeroPoint — per case (gym channel)</h3>
  <table class="table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>SKU</th>
        <th class="r">Retail</th>
        <th class="r">COGS</th>
        <th class="r">Margin</th>
        <th class="r yellow">Fred 20%</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {
        zeropoint.map((s) => {
          const c = commission(s);
          return (
            <tr>
              <td>{s.label}</td>
              <td class="r">{$(s.retail)}</td>
              <td class="r">{$(s.cogs)}</td>
              <td class="r">{$(c.margin)}</td>
              <td class="r yellow"><strong>{$(c.fred)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
          );
        })
      }
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="micro">
    Both ZeroPoint formats are on offer to gyms. The gym picks based on how their
    spray stations are set up — 4×1 gallon for portability, 2×2.5 gallon for
    fewer changeouts.
  </p>

  <h2>Subscriptions — where it actually compounds</h2>
  <p>
    Subscription is the whole point of the gym channel. Most of the value isn't
    a single $96 case sale — it's a gym that puts JockShock on every athlete's
    locker hook and ZeroPoint on every spray station, set to auto-ship every
    month, for years. Every shipment pays you.
  </p>
  <p>
    We give a <strong>10% discount</strong> on subscription orders. Your
    commission is 20% of contribution margin <em>on the discounted price</em> —
    every shipment, for as long as the sub is active. No expiration, no clawback,
    no "first sale only." If they keep ordering, you keep getting paid.
  </p>

  <table class="table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Subscription SKU</th>
        <th class="r">Sub price (10% off)</th>
        <th class="r yellow">Fred per shipment</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {
        [...jockshock.slice(1, 2), ...zeropoint].map((s) => {
          const c = commission(s, 0.10);
          return (
            <tr>
              <td>{s.label} — monthly</td>
              <td class="r">{$(c.sale)}</td>
              <td class="r yellow"><strong>{$(c.fred)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
          );
        })
      }
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>What this looks like in real money</h2>
  <p>
    The gym subscription is the <em>anchor</em> — every gym you sign produces
    paired-program revenue every month, forever. But the real upside is the
    athletes <strong>inside</strong> those gyms. Every gym you bring on gets
    its own referral code (something like <code>FRED-GYMNAME20</code>) — gym
    members use it for <strong>20% off</strong> their personal JockShock
    orders, and you earn 20% commission on every one of those too.
  </p>
  <p>
    Sign a gym, the gym anchors. The members compound. Both pay you, recurring,
    every month.
  </p>

  <h3>The full picture — gym subs + athlete pull-through</h3>

  {(() => {
    const jsSub = commission(jockshock[1], 0.10).fred;
    const zpSub = commission(zeropoint[0], 0.10).fred;
    const perGymBase = jsSub + zpSub; // ~$17.60/mo per gym from the paired sub
    const memberDtc = commission(jockshock[1], 0.20).fred; // ~$6.39 per member 3-pack at 20% off
    const scenarios = [
      { gyms: 5,   members: 150, conv: 0.05, note: "Pilot — first 90 days" },
      { gyms: 20,  members: 150, conv: 0.05, note: "Year-1 base case" },
      { gyms: 50,  members: 200, conv: 0.07, note: "Stretch — Year 1 finish" },
      { gyms: 100, members: 200, conv: 0.08, note: "Year 2 — full network" },
      { gyms: 250, members: 200, conv: 0.10, note: "What this can become" },
    ];
    return (
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Scenario</th>
            <th class="r">Sub residual / mo</th>
            <th class="r">Athlete sales / mo</th>
            <th class="r yellow">Total per year</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {scenarios.map((s) => {
            const subIncome = perGymBase * s.gyms;
            const athletesBuying = s.gyms * s.members * s.conv;
            const athleteIncome = athletesBuying * memberDtc;
            const totalMonthly = subIncome + athleteIncome;
            return (
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <strong>{s.gyms} gyms</strong>
                  <span class="row-note">
                    {" "}· {s.members} members · {Math.round(s.conv * 100)}% buy/mo · {s.note}
                  </span>
                </td>
                <td class="r">{$(subIncome)}</td>
                <td class="r">{$(athleteIncome)}</td>
                <td class="r yellow"><strong>{$(totalMonthly * 12)}</strong></td>
              </tr>
            );
          })}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    );
  })()}

  <p class="micro">
    Member counts are conservative. A real CrossFit box has 200–400 members. A
    BJJ academy has 150–300. A D1 Training franchise — your home turf — runs
    bigger. The 5–10% monthly purchase rate is a low bar: these are athletes
    already paying $200+/month for gym access. They drop $60 on gear spray
    without thinking about it once they see the trainer using it.
  </p>

  <h3>What drives the athlete-sales line</h3>
  <p>
    The bigger your network, the bigger the multiplier. At 250 gyms with 200
    members each averaging 10% monthly purchase rate, the athlete-sales
    line alone is over <strong>{$(commission(jockshock[1], 0.20).fred * 250 * 200 * 0.10)}</strong>
    per month — every month, recurring as long as those gyms stay active. That's
    not the ceiling either. Some scenarios that aren't in the table:
  </p>
  <ul class="bullets">
    <li>
      <strong>Athlete subscriptions.</strong> Once a member buys their first
      3-pack with the gym's code, they get pulled into the same 60-day reorder
      flow as everyone else. The conversion to subscription means recurring
      commission on athletes, not just one-time pops.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>ZeroPoint upgrades.</strong> A growing gym graduates from 4×1G
      to 2×2.5G to a 275-gallon tote ($3,600 retail). Your commission scales
      with that.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>One-time bulk orders.</strong> Pre-season for a high school
      football program, season-start for a club soccer org, a college team
      buyer — these are large single-PO sales on top of the recurring base.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Direct DTC sales you drive personally.</strong> Anything you
      bring in through your own audience, posts, or events — full commission,
      same rate.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The table above is the gym channel <em>floor</em>. Add everything else on top.
  </p>

  <h2>How leads route</h2>
  <p>
    Every form submission on <code>/teams</code> (and <code>/gyms</code> when we
    rename it) routes to your inbox first. Mike copied. You're primary on every
    gym lead — you decide who you call, when, what the deal looks like.
  </p>
  <p>
    DTC orders that come in through the public site flow normally; commission on
    those is split based on referral attribution. If a gym you signed sends their
    athletes to JockShock with the gym's discount code, you earn on those orders
    too.
  </p>

  <h2>How you get paid</h2>
  <ul class="bullets">
    <li>
      <strong>Source of truth: Nexus.</strong> All your commissions calculate
      automatically against the live <code>products.standard_cost</code> in
      Nexus and the actual order data. Nothing is hand-tracked.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cadence: monthly.</strong> Report runs the first business day of
      the month for the prior month. Payment follows the report.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The report is auditable.</strong> Every commission line ties to a
      specific Shopify order ID, the SKU on that order, the COGS Nexus had at
      the time of the order, and the fee Shopify charged. You can reconcile any
      single dollar to a single transaction.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Numbers move when COGS moves.</strong> Sprayer cost goes up, your
      commission per bottle goes down (slightly). Conversely, every time we cut
      input cost or improve packout, your commission goes up. Same math for
      everyone.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>First 90 days</h2>
  <ul class="bullets">
    <li>
      <strong>Goal: 5 paying gyms on the paired subscription.</strong> Five
      anchor accounts gives us a real read on what the program looks like at
      scale and gives you a recurring base to build on.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>What we'll build for you.</strong> Sales sheet (one-pager you can
      hand a gym owner), pricing card with subscription math, simple
      sample-shipment workflow so you can drop product without filling out a
      form for every demo.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>What we expect from you.</strong> Honest reads on the field. If a
      gym says "wrong size case" or "wrong cadence" or "too expensive" — tell
      us. The product spec and the program structure are both still pliable.
      The math isn't.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The non-negotiables</h2>
  <ul class="bullets">
    <li>
      <strong>Stick to the deodorizer story.</strong> No kill claims, no
      "antimicrobial," no EPA references, no duration-of-protection language.
      We don't substantiate any of it on the JockShock label, so we can't say
      it in front of a customer. ZeroPoint is registered separately and has
      different rules — but this page is JockShock-first.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No off-the-books pricing.</strong> Don't quote a price below
      Shopify's price card without checking with Mike. We can do volume deals;
      they need to come through the system so commission calc stays clean.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>If a gym refuses to subscribe, that's fine.</strong> We have a
      one-time order option. Subscription is the goal because it compounds for
      both of us, but a one-time gym is better than no gym.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p class="signoff">— Mike</p>

